name>Mills</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF042183%2F1"><gtr:id>44BE0350-20BA-4FAD-9CE2-5834C8718E84</gtr:id><gtr:title>Framing the Medical Market: Medical Advertisements in Colonial North India, c.1900-1947</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F042183/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>My Visiting Fellow, Dr Madhuri Sharma of Delhi University, will focus on a programme of research that involves an analysis of medical advertisements in the period c.1850-1947 to frame the interconnections between medical practice, drug manufacturers and the medical market in colonial North India. The work will explore three interlinked themes: (1) the advertising strategies of European and Indian medical entrepreneurs who competed in the changing medical market; (2) how the changing market conditions impacted upon indigenous practitioners, including the imperatives of professionalisation and the adoption of new forms of medical practice; and (3) the social context of the projection of products and creation of consumers.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />The two main research questions for the fellowship programme will be:
&lt;br />
&lt;br />
&lt;ol>
 &lt;li>What strategies were adopted by European and Indian companies and entrepreneurs to create consumers for their products and to edge out their competitors?&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>What this tells us about the transformation of the medical market in herbs and drugs over this period?&lt;/li>
&lt;/ol>The aim will be to correlate the analysis of medical advertisements with their societal context, while engaging with current historiographical interest in the medical market and issues of medical professionalization.
&lt;br />
